AVGO discloses $20.5 billion of remaining performance obligations—about 43 % to be recognized as revenue over the next 12 months—showing that its unearned revenue is anchored in multi‑year semiconductor contracts with firm customer commitments and is largely insulated from short‑term termination, a fact highlighted in its 10‑K performance‑obligations table;  
CRM’s acquisition‑risk narrative stresses that integrating new businesses can erode acquired unearned revenue and forces the company to re‑allocate resources and adjust revenue‑recognition policies, directly tying the stability of its deferred income to the success of its M&A strategy;  
and MSFT lists $3.7 billion of unearned revenue in its deferred‑income‑tax‑asset schedule, using that balance to offset future tax liabilities and to reflect the recurring subscription and cloud income that forms the backbone of its long‑term financial outlook.

ACN quantifies its long‑term investment exposure through the “Long‑Term Investments (FIN_METRIC)” metric, reporting a $29 million net gain in accumulated other comprehensive loss that will be re‑classified to cost of services and a $693 million potential loss from a 10 % foreign‑exchange move, while noting its private‑equity stakes are immaterial;  

MSFT, linked to this metric via the KG relationship “Long‑Term Investments (ORG) → MSFT (ORG)”, discloses the fair‑value of its long‑term investments and related unrealized losses across the <12‑month and ≥12‑month buckets, with an estimated $8.38 billion fair value of long‑term debt and minimal derivative use, reflecting a risk‑management focus on transparent market‑value reporting;  

TXN’s exposure is expressed indirectly through uncertain tax‑position liabilities of $69 million (2021) and $89 million (2020) recorded in other long‑term liabilities (and associated deferred tax assets), showing that its long‑term risk strategy centers on tax‑compliance reserves rather than investment‑related hedging.
